1 1. Retail sales. Notwithstanding any provision of this Title to the contrary, a person
2 licensed to sell wine for on-premises or off-premises consumption may also sell low-
3 alcohol spirits products and spirits cocktail products. All provisions of this Title applicable
4 to wine, except chapters 65 and 67, apply to low-alcohol spirits products and spirits cocktail
5 products when sold by persons licensed to sell wine for on-premises or off-premises
6 consumption.
7 2. Wholesale sales. Notwithstanding any provision of this Title to the contrary, a
8 person licensed under section 1401 as an in-state wholesaler of wine may also sell and
9 distribute low-alcohol spirits products and spirits cocktail products.
10 Sec. 4. 28-A MRSA §1355-A, sub-§5, ¶D, as amended by PL 2021, c. 658, §226,
11 is further amended to read:
12 D. Except for spirits cocktail products and as otherwise provided in this section, spirits
13 produced by a holder of a distillery or small distillery license must be sold to the State
14 and are subject to the listing, pricing and distribution provisions of this Title.
15 Sec. 5. 28-A MRSA §1355-A, sub-§5, ¶F-1, as amended by PL 2023, c. 34, §5,
16 is further amended to read:
17 F-1. A distillery or small distillery may sell to the public for on-premises consumption
18 cocktails containing samples of a spirits cocktail product and spirits produced by the
19 distillery or small distillery under the conditions specified in this paragraph.
20 (1) A spirits cocktail product or a cocktail containing spirits may be sold only at
21 the manufacturing facility where the a spirits cocktail product and spirits are
22 produced or at an additional location licensed under paragraph B, subparagraph
23 (3).
24 (2) The distillery or small distillery may include wine or spirits not manufactured
25 by the distillery or small distillery as an ingredient in the cocktail only if the
26 distillery or small distillery purchased the wine or spirits from an agency liquor
27 store licensed as a reselling agent. This subparagraph does not apply to spirits
28 cocktail products.
29 (3) A cocktail may not contain more than 4 1/2 ounces of spirits.
30 Sec. 6. 28-A MRSA §1355-A, sub-§5, ¶G, as amended by PL 2021, c. 658, §226,
31 is further amended to read:
32 G. Notwithstanding paragraph D, a holder of a small distillery license that sells its
33 products spirits directly to consumers for off-premises consumption under paragraph
34 B, subparagraph (3), subsection 2, paragraph D or subsection 2, paragraph I,
35 subparagraph (4‑A) may pay the bureau the difference between the distillery's price
36 charged to the bureau and the discounted retail price charged by the bureau under
37 section 606, subsection 4‑B. A small distillery is not required to transport spirits that
38 will be sold for off-premises consumption as described in this paragraph to a warehouse
39 operated by the bureau or by a wholesale spirits provider. A holder of a small distillery
40 license shall record the quantity of spirits sold for off-premises consumption that were
41 not transported to a warehouse as described in this paragraph and submit monthly
42 reports of this information, along with the full amount of state liquor tax due as
